## Phase 3: The Nervous System (Backend & Database Communication)

### 1. API Routes & Data Fetchers (`lib/newsApi.ts`)
The `lib/newsApi.ts` file acts as the primary data gateway. It constructs URLs using the `NEXT_PUBLIC_PULSE_API_URL` environment variable (falling back to `http://localhost:8000`).

*   **`fetchNewsByCategory(category, page, limit)`**
    *   **Endpoint:** `GET /api/news/{category}?page={page}&limit={limit}`
    *   **Purpose:** Fetches the paginated news feed for any given category string.
    *   **Data Schema Reconciled:** The frontend strictly expects `data.articles` to return an Array of `Article` objects containing fields like `title`, `description`, `url`, `image_url`, `published_at`, `source`. It enforces `cache: 'no-store'` to ensure real-time bypassing of the Next.js cache.
*   **`searchNews(query)`**
    *   **Endpoint:** `GET /api/search?q={encodedQuery}`
    *   **Purpose:** Queries the backend search index. Returns the same `Article[]` array format.
*   **Missing Data Handling:** If the backend routes untagged articles to a generic 'News Articles' collection, the frontend API agnostic setup handles it perfectly. As long as the backend returns the `Article` schema, the frontend `NewsCard` safely ignores missing tags via `category={article.category || ''}`.

### 2. Server vs. Client Demarcation
The entire UI-1 Pulse application has aggressively pivoted towards **Client Components**.

*   **The Client Dominance:** Almost every major page in `app/(pulse)/` including `page.tsx` (Homepage), `news/page.tsx` (Feed), and `search/page.tsx` (Search) explicitly declares `'use client';` at the very top.
*   **Forced Dynamic Rendering:** In `news/page.tsx` and `search/page.tsx`, the code explicitly exports `export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic';`. This is because they rely on `useSearchParams()` from `next/navigation` to read URL queries (like `?category=x`).
*   **Why No Server Components?** Because the UI-1 architecture heavily relies on infinite scrolling (`useInfiniteScroll`) and dynamic user interaction (like tracking view counts on hover), rendering these feeds on the server was abandoned in favor of Client-Side Fetching inside `useEffect` blocks. 

### 3. Analytics & Mutations (Stats Pipeline)
The analytics pipeline handles mutations (writes) via the `lib/analytics.ts` file. This was migrated from Firebase to direct backend (Appwrite) calls.

*   **`incrementArticleView()`**
    *   **Triggered By:** `ArticleDetailView.tsx` when a user opens an article.
    *   **Endpoint:** `POST /api/engagement/articles/{id}/view`
    *   **Payload:** It sends a JSON body containing real data to allow the backend to auto-create the document if it doesn't exist in the database:
        ```json
        {
            "url": "article-url.com/...",
            "title": "Article Title",
            "image": "image-url.com/...",
            "category": "ai"
        }
        ```
*   **`getArticleStats()` & `getArticleViewCount()`**
    *   **Endpoint:** `GET /api/engagement/articles/{id}/stats?category={category}`
    *   **Caching Mechanism:** Unlike the news feed, analytics uses a robust local memory cache (`statsCache.get()`) with a strict `CACHE_TTL` of 60 seconds to prevent hammering the backend with view-count requests during intense scrolling.

### 4. External Integrations (Newsletter & Audio)
These features utilize separate backend namespaces to handle complex external logic.

*   **Newsletter Subscription (`NewsletterSubscribe.tsx`)**
    *   **Endpoint:** `POST /api/subscription/subscribe`
    *   **Trigger:** Submitted via the email capture form in the `NewsletterModal`.
    *   **Payload:** 
        ```json
        {
            "email": "user@example.com",
            "name": "User Name",
            "topics": ["news", "ai", "security", "cloud"]
        }
        ```
*   **Audio Generation (`AudioPlayer.tsx`)**
    *   **Endpoint:** `POST /api/audio/generate`
    *   **Trigger:** Triggered when a user clicks the Play button on an article card where `audio_url` is not already cached.
    *   **Payload:** It sends the complete article context to the backend so the backend scraper/AI can generate the TTS (Text-to-Speech) file:
        ```json
        {
            "article_url": "...",
            "title": "...",
            "image_url": "...",
            "category": "..."
        }
        ```
    *   **Response Handling:** It specifically expects `data.success` (boolean) and `data.audio_url` (string) to instantly swap the `<audio>` source and begin playback.

